          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-stacc">theStacc vs Yoast SEO — where we are honestly better (and worse)</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Feature</th><th>Yoast SEO</th><th>theStacc</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>Starting price</td><td class="cell-yes">Free (or $99/yr Premium)</td><td>$99/mo</td></tr>
              <tr><td>WordPress on-page optimisation</td><td class="cell-yes">Best-in-class</td><td>Built-in for theStacc articles</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Schema markup generator</td><td class="cell-yes">Comprehensive</td><td class="cell-yes">Auto-applied</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Keyword research / SERP analysis</td><td class="cell-no">None (Semrush integration only)</td><td class="cell-yes">Built into every article</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Articles written for you</td><td class="cell-no">No — you write the content</td><td class="cell-yes">30 / month</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Auto-publishes to your CMS</td><td>Plugin only — you click Publish</td><td class="cell-yes">Scheduled auto-publishing</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Google Business Profile posts</td><td class="cell-no">Not included (Local add-on is on-site only)</td><td class="cell-yes">30 GBP posts / month</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Social media posts</td><td class="cell-no">Only controls how shared links appear</td><td class="cell-yes">30 posts / month</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Off-WordPress (Webflow, Ghost)</td><td class="cell-no">WordPress only</td><td class="cell-yes">All major CMSes</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Real monthly cost (plugin + writers + research)</strong></td><td>$2,500–$7,800</td><td><strong>$99 flat</strong></td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Where Yoast wins:</strong> if you have a WordPress site, you should install it (or RankMath). It is the right tool for on-page WordPress configuration. <strong>Where theStacc wins:</strong> if your job is producing the content Yoast scores, not just scoring it.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Yoast SEO?</h2>
        <p>Yoast SEO is a WordPress plugin that handles on-page SEO inside the WordPress editor. Founded by Joost de Valk in 2010, it now powers 12 million+ WordPress sites and maintains a 4.8/5 rating across 27,500+ WordPress.org reviews. Yoast was acquired by Newfold Digital in 2021.</p>

        <p>The plugin does six core things:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Focus keyword scoring</strong> — the iconic green/orange/red traffic light system</li>
          <li><strong>Readability analysis</strong> — Flesch reading ease, passive voice, sentence length, transition words</li>
          <li><strong>Schema.org markup</strong> — Article, FAQ, HowTo, Local Business, Product schema</li>
          <li><strong>XML sitemaps</strong> — auto-generated and submitted to Google</li>
          <li><strong>Meta tag control</strong> — title, description, OG image, canonical, robots</li>
          <li><strong>Breadcrumbs</strong> — output via shortcode or theme integration</li>
        </ol>

        <p>What Yoast is <em>not</em>: a content writer, a keyword research tool, a backlink analyser, or a tool that works outside WordPress.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>Joost de Valk founded Yoast in 2010. The plugin was acquired by Newfold Digital (parent of Bluehost and HostGator) in 2021. Joost remains involved as Chief Product Officer. The free plugin has been continuously developed for 16 years — making it one of the longest-lived SEO products of any kind.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">Yoast SEO features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>

        <h3>1. Focus keyword scoring (the traffic light)</h3>
        <p>Enter a focus keyword. Yoast scores your post on 20+ on-page signals: keyword in title, keyword in URL, keyword density, keyword in subheadings, keyword in image alt text, internal links, outbound links, meta description, and more. The traffic light (green / orange / red) is the most copied UI in SEO software history.</p>

        <h3>2. Readability analysis</h3>
        <p>Calculates Flesch reading ease, flags overlong sentences, marks passive-voice instances, highlights paragraphs that need transition words, and warns about repeated sentence beginnings. Best-in-class beginner education for new writers — the warnings teach you what to fix.</p>

        <h3>3. Schema.org markup</h3>
        <p>Auto-generates Article schema on every post. Supports FAQ, HowTo, and breadcrumb blocks in the Gutenberg editor. Premium adds Local Business schema, Person schema, and more comprehensive Article variants. Validation against Google's Rich Results test is consistently clean.</p>

        <h3>4. XML sitemaps + breadcrumbs</h3>
        <p>Auto-generated sitemap index split by post type. Auto-pings Google when content changes. Breadcrumb output works with most themes via shortcode or template tag.</p>

        <h3>5. Premium features ($99/yr)</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Internal linking suggestions</strong> — recommends related posts to link to as you write</li>
          <li><strong>Multiple focus keywords</strong> — score one post against up to 5 keywords</li>
          <li><strong>Redirect manager</strong> — handle 301s, 302s without editing .htaccess</li>
          <li><strong>Stale content detection</strong> — surfaces posts that haven't been updated in 12 months</li>
          <li><strong>Semrush integration</strong> — related keyword suggestions inside the editor</li>
          <li><strong>24/7 support</strong> — real human responses, generally same-day</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>6. Add-ons (each $79/yr)</h3>
        <p>Local SEO (Google Business profile sync, store locator schema). Video SEO (video sitemap, OpenGraph for video). News SEO (Google News sitemap). WooCommerce SEO (product schema, brand archives). Premium Plus bundles all add-ons for $229/year.</p>

        <h2 id="pricing">Yoast SEO pricing — what it really costs in 2026</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Plan</th><th>Price</th><th>Sites</th><th>Internal linking</th><th>Multiple keywords</th><th>Add-ons</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Free</strong></td><td>$0</td><td>Unlimited</td><td class="cell-no">No</td><td class="cell-no">1 keyword</td><td class="cell-no">No</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Premium</strong></td><td>$99 / year</td><td>1 site</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td class="cell-yes">Up to 5</td><td>Available separately</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Premium Plus</strong></td><td>$229 / year</td><td>1 site</td><td class="cell-yes">Yes</td><td class="cell-yes">Up to 5</td><td class="cell-yes">All included</td></tr>
